{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Combinators","slug":"css-combinators","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Selectors"],"learning_objectives":["Descendant Selector (space)","Child Selector (>)","Adjacent Sibling Selector (+)","General Sibling Selector (~)"],"theory":"A combinator is something that explains the relationship between the selectors.\n\n*   **Descendant selector (space)**: Matches all elements that are descendants of a specified element.\n*   **Child selector (>)**: Matches all elements that are children (direct descendants) of a specified element.\n*   **Adjacent sibling selector (+)**: Matches an element that is directly after another specific element.\n*   **General sibling selector (~)**: Matches all elements that are next siblings of a specified element.","syntax":"div p { background-color: yellow; }     /* Descendant */\ndiv > p { background-color: yellow; }   /* Child */\ndiv + p { background-color: yellow; }   /* Adjacent */\ndiv ~ p { background-color: yellow; }   /* General Sibling */","examples":[{"code":"/* Indent only paragraphs that come after a heading */\nh1 + p {\n  font-weight: bold;\n}","output":"Only the first paragraph after an h1 is bold.","explanation":"Useful for standardizing typography flow."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Confusing Child (>) and Descendant (space)","correction":"Descendant goes infinitely deep. Child stops at the first level.","example":"If you have <div><section><p>...</p></section></div>: `div p` works. `div > p` fails."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What does the `+` selector do?","answer":"It selects the element immediately following the specified element (must be a sibling).","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Select all <p> elements that are direct children of <div>.","hint":"Use >","solution":"div > p { ... }","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Breadcrumbs","d